//A triangular cubic bezier patch, bound by 6 CV-heights, 
//is tranceable analytically with good performance and precision
//for no good reason i never bothered to fix the camera of /XsjSDt, till now
//and i notice that this shader sucks if the camera is inside the bezier-triangle-prism.

//it works fine, as long as the patch is not too planar
//any near-planar bezierPatch has a too small determinant which diminishes precision too much.
//the first few milliseconds of this demo are near-planar

//it works fine as long as the camera is not inside the bounding-prism (incl min&&max height) 
//of the bezier patch

//But if the camera is inside the bezierPrism, the roots are in the wrong order. 
//and it seems to treat roots behind the camera as if they are infront of the camera??


//BUT it always renders 2 patches, and their distance to each other is the distance of the camera to vec3(0)
//, as if they are mirror images.
//and they intersect when the camera is close to it.
//, and they appear to swap places when you move over one of them.
//and then you may confuse it for its mirror image.
//unless you have the original inside its AABV

//the open question here is, how to remove the mirror image solution?



float segment(vec2 P, vec2 A, vec2 B){ 
    vec2 g=B-A;
    vec2 h=P-A;
    return length(h-g*clamp(dot(g,h)/dot(g,g),0.,1.));}

