// Standard FDTD vs. fourth order FDTD

// Finite Difference Time-Domain (FDTD) methods are a family of numerical schemes
// which allow to compute wave propagation on a regular grid.
// They compute an approximate solution of the wave equation 
// by using approximate formulas for the partial derivatives.
// The results therefore contain some errors, mostly in the form of "dispersion",
// which manifests itself as a "ripple" effect.
//
// The most common version of FDTD uses second-order approximation in space and time using
// five neighboring samples (the current pixel and its four neighbors).
// This results in strong dispersion when fewer than about 20 points per wavelength are used.
// The use of a finer grid allows to reduce this dispersion error, at an increased computational cost.
//
// Another way to reduce the dispersion error is to use higher-order methods.
// Higher-order methods compute a more accurate approximation of the partial derivatives by looking
// at more samples.
// They allow to use fewer points per wavelength, at the cost of an increased number of operations
// per point.
//
// The scheme implemented here is a fourth order FDTD, as described by Shubin and Bell in 1987.
// The computation uses a 14-point stencil.
//
// The displayed graphics compare the two techniques: standard FDTD is shown in red,
// whereas fourth-order FDTD is shown in green.
// In the beginning they overlap; however, they very soon start to diverge, as numerical
// dispersion spoils the results of the second-order method faster: this is indicated
// by the presence of red ripples.
//
// Note that the simulation results depend on the screen resolution: higher resolution will
// make both methods more accurate, so that it will take more time before they start to look
// different. Conversely, at small resolutions, they will start differing almost instantly.

Main {
    float v4 = A(U).x;
    float v2 = A(U).z;

    // Red is standard (second order), green is fourth order
    vec4 col = vec4(100,0,0,0) * abs(v2) + vec4(0,100,0,0) * abs(v4);
    Q = mix(vec4(0.5), col, isInDomain(uu(U)));
}

